private hazmat company (Power Services Company) based in Greeley, Colorado. If a release were to occur the following response practices are to be implemented: 

Incidental Releases (Small Discharge Scenario)

A release is considered an incidental release and does not require immediately notifying the Plant Manager or the EH&S Manager if the following is true:

A¿	The released hazardous substance can be absorbed or otherwise controlled at the time of release by employees or other trained persons present;
A¿	The release is either inside or outside facility buildings, within secondary containment, on an impervious surface and does not reach pervious surfaces (i.e., soil) or storm water drainage;
A¿	The released hazardous material is less than 25 gallons;
A¿	The release would not have posed a threat to human health and the environment if the release had not been immediately controlled.
		
		In response to an incidental release, the following steps will be taken:

1.	If an employee observes a release, the employee will immediately notify a supervisor who will then assess the release.  The employee and/or supervisor may attempt to stop the flow of product if doing so poses no threat or harm.  If the supervisor decides the release does not constitute a threat to human health or the environment and does not require assistance by personnel outside the immediate area of the spill, then clean-up will begin.
2.	The supervisor or assigned trained personnel will clean-up the spill.  Employees or trained personnel cleaning up the spill will be attired in the necessary personal protective equipment (i.e., goggles, material-compatible synthetic gloves, boots, etc.).  If necessary, clean-up will be preceded by an attempt to stop the discharge, restricting traffic through the spill area, and limiting migration of the release by laying berms of absorbent materials.
